── SECTION 4: 5h SLIDING WINDOWS BY DOMINANT MODEL ────────────────────

  A window is labeled "4.6" or "4.7" if >50% of calls use that model.
  Only considers windows starting from Apr 2 (fair comparison span).

  Dominant | Windows | Mean Util | p50 Util | p90 Util | p99 Util | Max Util | >80% | >100%
  ---------|---------|-----------|----------|----------|----------|----------|------|------
       4.6 |     963 |     45.8% |    15.0% |   132.1% |   574.6% |   630.6% |  173 |   147
       4.7 |     174 |     19.8% |     7.1% |    59.1% |   104.1% |   110.8% |    7 |     7

  Mean utilization 4.7 / 4.6 ratio: 0.43x
  p90  utilization 4.7 / 4.6 ratio: 0.45x

── KEY FINDINGS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  1. Per-call aggregate multipliers (4.7 vs 4.6):
       input      0.09x
       output     2.61x
       cache_read 1.20x
       iter-call share delta: 20.9 pp

  2. DO NOT OVER-READ THESE AS "4.7 EFFECTS".
     The daily breakdown in Section 3 shows 4.6 has massive within-span
     variance in per-call averages (e.g. input 1.9-93 tokens, cache_read
     41K-233K across Apr 2-15 on 4.6 alone). The aggregate multipliers
     are confounded with workload-mix differences between spans.

     The Apr 10-15 4.6 tail (closest workload to 4.7 window) has avg input
     2-14 tokens — continuous with the 4.7 range of 2-5. So "input 0.10x"
     is an averaging artifact from including early-April heavy-input days.

  3. WHAT THIS DATASET CAN AND CANNOT SAY:
     Can say: 4.6 and 4.7 both show low-input, cache_read-dominated profiles.
              Iter-call share differs between spans (57.9% vs 78.8%).
     Cannot say: whether tokenizer-inflation or Q5h-burn claims in
                 16_OPUS-47-ADVISORY.md are corroborated at per-call
                 granularity. Sample too small, workload too variable.
                 A workload-matched comparison (same task repeated on
                 both models) is the right test.

  4. Sample sizes: 4.6 32299 calls, 4.7 2615 calls.
